<LP>
   MICHAEL MILKEN PLEADED guilty to six felony counts, as
expected, capping a three-year probe of securities fraud and
other crimes by Drexel's former junk bond chief. Milken, once
the world's most-powerful financier, also agreed to pay $600
million in fines and restitution and to cooperate with the
continuing federal inquiry. He will be sentenced Oct. 1 and
faces up to 28 years in prison.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sears Roebuck's profit plunged 59% in the first quarter
due to "unsatisfactory" results in its core retail business
and hefty claims at its Allstate insurance unit. Sears stock
slid $1.125, to $35.375, a 52-week low.
   ---
   IBM will introduce several low-cost home computers this
summer, making a fresh assault on a market where it has done
poorly in the past.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco posted a $222 million loss for the first
quarter, reflecting huge debt costs. But the food and tobacco
giant showed strong gains in operating earnings and cash
flow.
   ---
   Western Union said it will file a recapitalization plan
involving an exchange offer of new secured debt and common
stock. The company is trying to avoid a Chapter 11 filing.
   ---
   Durable goods orders surged 6.7% in March, prompting some
analysts to suggest manufacturing may be rebounding. The
rise, reflecting a jump in transporation-equipment orders,
was the biggest in more than a year.
                                                                                                       

   Sales of U.S.-built cars and trucks plunged 17.7% in
mid-April, a poor performance in what is usually the heart of
the spring selling season.
   ---
   The film industry and other producers of copyrighted
material were dealt a blow by the Supreme Court, which ruled
the re-release of "Rear Window" violated copyright law.
   ---
   Quaker Oats decided to spin off its troubled Fisher-Price
toy business, allowing management to focus on problems in its
foods business.
   ---
   Salomon and Morgan Stanley had stronger quarterly results,
mainly due to bond-trading windfalls. But the securities
firms didn't escape the weakness in investment banking.
   ---
   Ames Department Stores stocks and bonds tumbled further
amid growing speculation the chain may seek Chapter 11
protection.
   ---
   The nation's mortgage lenders were accused by seven states
of violating federal law by requiring homeowners to place
more money than necessary in escrow accounts.
   ---
   Short interest fell 1.3% among major OTC stocks for the
month ended April 12, while borrowed shares in smaller issues
rose 28.3%.
   ---
   Five oil companies posted mixed quarterly results that
reflected one-time items and higher crude prices.
   ---
   Labor costs rose 1.6% in the first quarter, fueled by
higher Social Security taxes and other benefits. Costs rose
1.1% in the previous quarter.
